Events from the year '''2001 in the [[European Union]]'''.
The year was designated the [[European Year of Languages]] by the [[Council of Europe]] and the [[European Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://europa.eu/legislation_summaries/education_training_youth/lifelong_learning/c11044_en.htm|title=European Year of Languages 2001|website=Europa.eu|publisher=European Union|date=6 December 2005|accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref>
==Incumbents== * '''[[President of the European Commission|Commission President]]''' — [[Romano Prodi]] * '''[[Presidency of the Council of the European Union|Council Presidency]]''' — [[Sweden]] (January–June), [[Belgium]] (July–December) * '''[[President of the European Parliament|Parliament President]]''' — [[Nicole Fontaine]] * '''[[High Representative for Common Foreign and Security Policy|High Representative]]''' — [[Javier Solana]]
==Events== * 1 January - ** [[Sweden]] takes over the [[Presidency of the European Union]]. ** [[Greece]] becomes the 12th member of the Eurozone.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/1095783.stm|title=Greece joins eurozone|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=1 January 2001|accessdate=23 November 2013}}</ref> * 5 March - The electorate of [[Switzerland]] vote by a wide margin against joining negotiations to enter the European Union.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/03/05/world/swiss-voters-solidly-reject-talks-on-joining-the-european-union.html|title=Swiss Voters Solidly Reject Talks On Joining the European Union|work=The New York Times|first=Elizabeth|last=Olsen|date=5 March 2001|accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref> * 7 June - In [[Irish constitutional referendums, 2001#Twenty-fourth Amendment|a referendum]], the electorate of [[Ireland]] votes against the [[Treaty of Nice]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/06/09/world/irish-vote-stalls-plan-to-expand-europe-s-union.html|title=Irish Vote Stalls Plan to Expand Europe's Union|newspaper=The New York Times|first=Sarah|last=Lyall|date=9 June 2001|accessdate=23 November 2013}}</ref> * 1 July - [[Belgium]] takes over the [[Presidency of the European Union]]. * 3 July - The [[European Commission]] blocks the proposed merger between American companies [[General Electric]] and [[Honeywell]], the first time European regulators have prevented such a move.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2001/BUSINESS/07/03/ge.eu/|title=EU kills GE-Honeywell|work=CNN|date=3 July 2001|accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref> * 20 September - In the wake of the [[September 11 attacks]], anti-terrorism measures such as EU-wide search and arrest warrants and the establishment of an anti-terrorism department within [[Europol]] are announced.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/1554718.stm|title=EU gears up to fight terrorism|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=20 September 2001|accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref> * 14 December - [[Euro]] coins first go on sale in banks in preparation for its public release into the Eurozone the following month.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2001/fyi/news/12/14/euro.coin/index.html|title=Euro coins go on sale|work=CNN|date=14 December 2001|accessdate=23 November 2013}}</ref>
