[[File:Executive_committee_of_the_American_Women's_War_Relief_Fund.jpg|alt=The executive committee of the American Women's War Relief Fund, circa 1914.|thumb|350x350px|The executive committee of the American Women's War Relief Fund, circa 1914.]] The '''American Women's War Relief Fund''' was an [[expatriate]] organization in the [[United Kingdom]] started by [[United States|American]] women to fund and aid [[World War I]] support efforts. The group was made up of wealthy [[Socialite|socialites]], politicians' wives and [[Humanitarianism|humanitarians]]. Many famous and well-connected women were involved, including [[Lou Henry Hoover|Lou Hoover]], [[Consuelo Vanderbilt]] and [[Lady Randolph Churchill]]. [[Louise Paget|Leila Paget]] served as president and [[Ava Lowle Willing]] was the fund's vice-president. The group, started almost immediately after the declaration of war, funded a fleet of [[Ambulance|ambulances]], two [[Hospital|hospitals]], one [[field hospital]] and several employment opportunities for unemployed women in Britain.
== History == The American Women's War Relief Fund was founded on August 5, 1914.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4fe9YQ-iMlEC&lpg=PA112&dq=%22american%20women's%20war%20relief%20fund%22&pg=PA112#v=onepage&q=%22american%20women's%20war%20relief%20fund%22&f=false|title=Excluded from the Record: Women, Refugees, and Relief, 1914-1929|last=Storr|first=Katherine|publisher=Peter Lang|year=2009|isbn=9783039118557|location=|pages=112|language=en}}</ref> Members of the organization were women from the [[United States]] who were married to [[English people|Englishmen]] and who wanted to help in the effort to support soldiers fighting in [[World War I]].{{sfn|Stanley|1915|p=11}} The president of the group was [[Louise Paget|Leila Paget]] and [[Ava Lowle Willing]] served as vice-president.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":3" /> Many of the members of the group had husbands who were commanding troops during the war.<ref name=":4">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19595784/|title=Every American Woman in England Working to Help Victims of War|last=Church|first=Hayden|date=6 October 1914|work=The Atlanta Constitution|access-date=2018-04-27|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Paget told journalist Hayden Church that she had thought up the idea for the Relief Fund merely three days after the start of the war.<ref name=":4" /> [[Winnaretta Singer]] and the Countess of Starfford were major donors of money to the fund.<ref name=":4" /> Paget also raised money in both America and England for wounded soldiers of several different countries fighting in the war.<ref name=":5">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19614489/|title=Women Found War Hospitals|last=|first=|date=21 June 1917|work=Harrisburg Telegraph|access-date=2018-04-27|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In 1917, there was an official request to have all American-led efforts to support the war in Europe be turned over to the [[American Red Cross]] for coordination purposes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19614763/|title=American Women's War Relief Fund|last=|first=|date=24 November 1917|work=Newspapers.com|access-date=2018-04-27|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In January 1918, the Relief Fund hospitals were fully turned over to be run by the Red Cross.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=https://americanwomeninwwi.wordpress.com/2017/01/09/helping-in-britain-the-american-womens-war-relief-fund/|title=Helping in Britain: The American Women’s War Relief Fund.|last=|first=|date=2017-01-09|work=American Women in World War I|access-date=2018-04-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927022703/https://americanwomeninwwi.wordpress.com/2017/01/09/helping-in-britain-the-american-womens-war-relief-fund/|archive-date=27 September 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>
The fund originally was going to sponsor an [[ambulance]] ship, but were persuaded to purchase 6 motor ambulances with a seventh added later by Grace Nichols and bearing the words, "From Friends in Boston".{{sfn|Tibbets|1916|p=123}} The ambulances had room enough for four [[Stretcher|stretchers]] and two medics.{{sfn|Tibbets|1916|p=123}}
== Hospitals == [[File:American_Women's_War_Relief_Hospital.jpg|thumb|The American Women's War Relief Hospital at Oldway in Paignton, Devon, 1914.]] In August 1914, the American Women's War Relief Fund received the donation from [[Paris Singer|Paris Eugene Singer]] of his Oldway House in [[Paignton]] to be used as a [[military hospital]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://americanwomenswarhospital.com/|title=The American Women's War Hospital at Oldway, Paignton 1914 to 1918|last=|first=|date=|website=The American Women's War Hospital|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180118094721/http://americanwomenswarhospital.com/|archive-date=18 January 2018|dead-url=|access-date=2018-04-26}}</ref> [[Lady Randolph Churchill]] was involved in persuading Singer to donate the house to use as a hospital.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-o6QppTwBpUC&lpg=PA307&dq=%22american%20women's%20war%20relief%20fund%22&pg=PA307#v=onepage&q=%22american%20women's%20war%20relief%20fund%22&f=false|title=American Jennie: The Remarkable Life of Lady Randolph Churchill|last=Sebba|first=Anne|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|year=2007|isbn=9780393079685|location=New York|pages=307|language=en}}</ref> The building, known as the American Women's War Hospital, was initially equipped with 200 beds, an [[Operating theater|operating theatre]], radiographic studio, [[pathology]] lab and also with [[Anesthesia|anesthetizing]] and [[Sterilization (medicine)|sterilization]] rooms.{{sfn|American Women's War Relief Fund|1915|p=6}} Later, an additional 20 beds were added, and an "Isolation Hut" for [[Quarantine|quarantines]] was built which could accommodate around 30 people.{{sfn|American Women's War Relief Fund|1915|p=6}} The [[American Red Cross]] helped staff the hospital, providing two units.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1914/11/07/archives/to-move-american-unit-physicians-and-nurses-going-to-hospital-at.html|title=TO MOVE AMERICAN UNIT.; Physicians and Nurses Going to Hospital at Paignton.|date=1914-11-07|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19596039/|title=Mrs. John Astor Asks Sympathy for England|last=|first=|date=4 March 1916|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-04-27|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The hospital began treating wounded soldiers as soon as September 1914.{{sfn|Tibbets|1916|p=121}} On November of that year, [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]] brought three hundred articles of clothes for the hospital and visited the wards.{{sfn|Tibbets|1916|p=122}}<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=January 1915|title=Word From the Front|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QgA9AAAAYAAJ&lpg=PA37&ots=xGmJq3FYE3&dq=%22american%20women's%20war%20relief%22&pg=PA38#v=onepage&q=%22american%20women's%20war%20relief%22&f=false|journal=The American Red Cross Magazine|volume=10|pages=37-38|via=}}</ref> Anita Strawbridge solicited donations such as socks and underwear from the [[United States]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19596197/|title=American Women Ask Clothing for Hospital|last=|first=|date=11 November 1914|work=The Philadelphia Inquirer|access-date=2018-04-27|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> By 1916, the American Women's War Hospital had treated 3,203 soldiers, according to the ''[[New York Herald]]''.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19587125/|title=Work of American Women's War Relief Fund in London|last=|first=|date=31 December 1916|work=New York Herald|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> By March 1919, when the hospital closed, it had served over 7,000 soldiers.<ref name=":2" />
The relief fund also provided partial funding for a [[field hospital]] in [[Belgium]] run by the wife of an officer, Mrs. O'Gorman.{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=66}} Another hospital, known as the American Women's Hospital, was located at [[Lancaster Gate]] and had been opened in 1917 by [[Walter Hines Page]] and [[Willa Alice Wilson Page]].<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19595598/|title=Two Hospitals for U.S. Troops Wounded|last=|first=|date=20 June 1917|work=Salisbury Evening Post|access-date=2018-04-27|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref name=":5" /> The Lancaster hospital had 41 beds and was mainly staffed with American nurses.<ref name=":5" /> It was inspected by King George and the Queen in 1917.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19615170/|title=Royalty Inspects Hospital|last=|first=|date=31 May 1917|work=Reading Times|access-date=2018-04-27|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> It closed in 1919.<ref name=":2" /> == Economic relief == In addition to setting up the hospital, the fund also created workrooms to teach young women new skills as part of the Economic Relief Committee of the American Women's War Relief Fund.{{sfn|Stanley|1915|p=12}}{{sfn|Tibbets|1916|p=124}} The committee was headed by [[Consuelo Vanderbilt]], who had been recruited by [[Lou Henry Hoover|Lou Hoover]] in 1915.{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=67}} This committee provided funds to pay the women's [[Wage|wages]] and articles of clothing, such as socks, were sent to the hospital or "given to soldiers and sailors in special need."<ref name=":1" /> A workroom was set up in a [[factory]] building near [[St Pancras, London|St. Pancras]] between August 1914 and August 1915.{{sfn|American Women's War Relief Fund|1915|p=28}} A [[knitting]] factory in [[Islington]] was opened in September 1914, followed by other workrooms in October at [[Woolwich]] and one at [[Greenwich]].{{sfn|American Women's War Relief Fund|1915|p=30}} The Woolwich factory was given to a charity to run in 1915.{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=67}} The women employed at the workrooms were not given quotas, but instead did what they were able to do.<ref name=":1" /> The working women were also given free [[Tea (meal)|tea]] and low cost meals in the evening.{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=66}}
== Notable members ==
* [[Lady Randolph Churchill]], chair of the hospital committee.<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":3" /> * [[Mary Ethel Harcourt]] (Mrs. Lewis Harcourt)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19587187/|title=American Women Give Aid|last=|first=|date=17 August 1914|work=The Sun|access-date=2018-04-26|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> * [[Lou Henry Hoover|Lou Hoover]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.history.com/topics/first-ladies/lou-hoover|title=Lou Hoover|last=|first=|date=|website=HISTORY.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309201255/https://www.history.com/topics/first-ladies/lou-hoover|archive-date=9 March 2018|dead-url=|access-date=2018-04-26}}</ref> * [[Ruth Bryan Owen]], secretary.<ref name=":2" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6-U8DwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA40&dq=%22american%20women's%20war%20relief%20fund%22&pg=PA40#v=onepage&q=%22american%20women's%20war%20relief%20fund%22&f=false|title=Ruth Bryan Owen: Congresswoman and Diplomat|last=Brown|first=Rudd|last2=Myers|first2=Paul A.|publisher=Paul Andrew Myers|year=2014|isbn=9781497442023|location=|pages=40|language=en}}</ref> * [[Louise Paget|Leila Paget]], president.<ref name=":0" /> * [[Consuelo Vanderbilt]] (the Duchess of Marlborough), chair of the Economic Relief Committee.{{sfn|Allen|2000|p=67}} * [[Ava Lowle Willing]], vice-president.<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3" /> * [[Willa Alice Wilson Page]].<ref name=":5" />
