{{wiktionary|antieuropeistico}}
{{wiktionary|Europhobia}}
'''Anti-Europeanism''' and '''Europhobia''' are political terms used in a variety of contexts, implying sentiment or policies in opposition to [[Europe]].

In the context of racial or ethno-nationalist politics, this may refer to the [[culture of Europe|culture]] or [[peoples of Europe|peoples]] of Europe (c.f. [[reverse racism|anti-white sentiment in the United States]]); 
In the shorthand of "Europe" standing for the [[European Union]] or [[European integration]], it may refer to [[Euroscepticism]], 
criticism of policies of European governments or the European Union.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/europhobia |title=Europhobia definition and meaning |publisher=Collins English Dictionary |date= |accessdate=2017-02-21}}</ref> 
In the context of United States foreign policy, it may refer to the geopolitical divide between "[[Transatlantic relations|transatlantic]]", "transpacific" and "hemispheric" (pan-American) relations.
The nominal antonyms would be ''[[pro-Europeanism]]'' or ''Europhilia''.{{clarify|date=October 2016}}

"Europhobia" is used of [[United Kingdom|British]] attitudes towards [[Continental Europe|the Continent]], either in the context of [[anti-German sentiment]] or of [[anti-Catholicism]],<ref>R. Miles in: Avril Horner (ed.), ''European Gothic: A Spirited Exchange 1760-1960'' (2002),  [https://books.google.ch/books?id=ofIS6ZAdsZAC&pg=PA84#v=onepage&q&f=false]
Thérèse Remus, ''Germanophobia, Europhobia, Xenophobia – About Stereotypes in Anglo-German Relations'' (2012)</ref>
or, more recently, of [[Euroscepticism in the United Kingdom]].

[[American exceptionalism]] in the United States<ref name=ae>[http://cadmus.eui.eu/bitstream/handle/1814/2767/04_25.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y Anti-Europeanism and Euroscepticism in the United States], Patrick Chamorel  No 25, EUI-RSCAS Working Papers from European University Institute (EUI), Robert Schuman Centre of Advanced Studies (RSCAS) 2004</ref> has long led to criticism of European [[domestic policy]] (such as the size of the [[welfare state]] in European countries)<ref>Elsner (2005), McPherson (2003)</ref> and [[foreign policy]] (such as European countries that did not support the US led [[2003 invasion of Iraq]]).<ref>Lexington (2007), Ash (2003)  Pipes (2006)</ref> The ideological split between reverence for European refinery and classics and an emerging anti-French and anti-European sentiment played already a role between [[John Adams]], [[Alexander Hamilton]] and their fellow Federalists, and [[Thomas Jefferson]] and other Democratic-Republicans urging closer ties.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}}

