*{{cite web |url= http://science.jrank.org/pages/10399/Nationalism-in-Africa-Postcolonial-Nationalism-in-Africa.html |title= Postcolonial Nationalism in Africa |author= [[Toyin Falola]] and Tyler Fleming |work= Science Encyclopedia, The History of Ideas Vol 4 |quote= [[African nationalism]] of the 1950s and 1960s was overtly anti[[Colonialism|colonial]] or anti-European. }}
*{{cite web |url= http://worldatwar.net/chandelle/v3/v3n1/frcoin.html |title= COIN: French Counter-Insurgency Aircraft, 1946-1965 |author= Robert Craig Johnson |work= The World at War |date= 1998 |quote= [[French rule in Algeria|Algeria]] presented [[French colonial empires|France]] with a set of tactical and political problems as different as the [[North Africa]]n terrain differed from that of [[French Indochina|Indochina]].  Politically, Algeria was an integral part of the [[France in the twentieth century|French Republic]] rather than a colony.  Its native [[Berber people|Berber]] and [[Arab people|Arab]] people were technically French citizens.  But discrimination was rife, and the [[White African|European immigrants]], the ''"[[Pied-noir|pieds-noirs]],"'' had a stranglehold on local government, owned most of the arable land, and controlled the [[police]].  When Arabs and Berbers were belatedly allowed to vote for half of a [[Constituent assembly|constituent provincial assembly]] in [[Nationalism and resistance in Algeria#Polarization and politicization|1948 and 1951]], blatant [[fraud]] gave the ''[[pied-noir]]'' candidates a sweeping victory. The resulting anti-European riots were savagely repressed at a cost of thousands of lives. }}
*{{cite web|url=http://www.swahilionline.com/features/articles/mazrui/mazrui7.htm |title=Between Terrorism and Wars of Liberation |author=Ali A. Mazrui |work=Swahili Online |date=1999 |quote=If anti-European and anti-[[Colonialism|colonial]] terrorism in Africa had produced good results in the end for Africa, [[Anti-Americanism|anti-American]] and [[Anti-Zionism|anti-Zionist]] terrorism in the Middle East has not yet found its moment of triumph.  Both the [[Middle East]] and [[Africa]] have been paying a price for the anti-American [[terrorism]]. The violent price which the Middle East is paying is obvious, especially in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], [[Iraq]] and in neighboring [[Afghanistan]].  What is the price which Africa is paying for terrorism against the [[United States]]? |authorlink=Ali Mazrui |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061111083457/http://www.swahilionline.com/features/articles/mazrui/mazrui7.htm |archivedate=2006-11-11 }}
