{{Infobox prepared food | name = Cepelinai | image = Cepelinai Sauce.JPG | image_size = 250px | caption = Cepelinai served with sour cream sauce and bacon bits | alternate_name = Didžkukuliai | country = [[Lithuania]] | region = | creator = | course = | type = [[Dumpling]] | served = | main_ingredient = [[Potato]]es, ground meat or dry [[cottage cheese]] ([[curd]]) or mushrooms | variations = | calories = | other = }} '''Cepelinai''' ({{abbrlink|lit.|literal translation}} 'zeppelins'; [[Grammatical number|singular]]: ''cepelinas'') or '''didžkukuliai''' is a traditional [[Lithuania]]n dish of stuffed potato [[dumpling]]s.<ref name="Jacob Ashkenazi 2014 p. 793">{{cite book | last=Jacob | first=J. | last2=Ashkenazi | first2=M. | title=The World Cookbook: The Greatest Recipes from Around the Globe, 2nd Edition &#91;4 Volumes&#93;: The Greatest Recipes from Around the Globe | publisher=ABC-CLIO | year=2014 | isbn=978-1-61069-469-8 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GmqEAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA793 | accessdate=November 5, 2016 | pages=793–794}}</ref> The dumplings are made from grated and riced [[potato]]es and stuffed with ground meat or dry [[Quark (dairy product)|curd cheese]] or mushrooms. It has been described as a [[national dish]] of Lithuania,<ref name="Albala 2011 p. 3-PA226">{{cite book | last=Albala | first=K. | title=Food Cultures of the World Encyclopedia | publisher=Greenwood | series=Food Cultures of the World Encyclopedia | issue=v. 1 | year=2011 | isbn=978-0-313-37626-9 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NTo6c_PJWRgC&pg=RA3-PA226 | accessdate=November 5, 2016 | page=3-PA226}}</ref><ref name="McLachlan 2008 p. 61">{{cite book | last=McLachlan | first=G. | title=Lithuania | publisher=Bradt Travel Guides | series=Bradt Guides | year=2008 | isbn=978-1-84162-228-6 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pDdqGoXvSvYC&pg=PA61 | accessdate=November 5, 2016 | page=61}}</ref> and is typically served as an entree.<ref name="Jacob Ashkenazi 2014 p. 793"/>
So named because their shape resembles that of a [[Zeppelin|Zeppelin airship]],<ref name="Jacob Ashkenazi 2014 p. 793"/> cepelinai are typically around 10–20&nbsp;cm long, although the size depends on where they are made: in the western [[Subdivisions of Lithuania|counties]] of Lithuania cepelinai are made bigger than in the east.{{Citation needed|date=January 2015}}
After boiling, the ''cepelinai'' are often served with [[sour cream]] sauce and [[bacon]] bits<ref name="Jacob Ashkenazi 2014 p. 793"/> or [[pork rind]]s.
In Poland, it is known as kartacz. It is a part of the cuisine of [[Podlachia]].
Similar dishes include Polish [[Pyzy (dish)|pyzy]], Swedish [[kroppkaka]], Acadian [[poutine râpée]], Norwegian [[raspeball]] and German [[Knödel|Kartoffelklöße]].
<gallery widths=200px heights=150px> File:Cepelinai 2, Vilnius, Lithuania - Diliff.jpg|Cepelinai with ground meat cut open File:Karmėlavos Cepelinas.JPG|Large cepelinas served with [[Pork rind|spirgai]] </gallery>
