'''Thelma Rodgers''' is a retired Antarctic scientist from New Zealand. She was the first woman to spend a winter at [[Scott Base]], New Zealand's scientific base in Antarctica.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scottbase50years.co.nz/faq/faq18.htm|title=Scott Base 50years|website=www.scottbase50years.co.nz|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref>
== Life == Rodgers grew up in the [[Nelson, New Zealand|Nelson]] area of the South Island of New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/world/2017/11/pioneering-antarctic-women-honoured-at-scott-base.html|title=Pioneering Antarctic women honoured at Scott Base|date=2017-11-13|work=Newshub|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en}}</ref> She worked as a science technician in the geophysics division of the [[Department of Scientific and Industrial Research (New Zealand)|Department of Scientific and Industrial Research]] and spent the winter at Scott Base in 1979. She was the first woman to winter-over at the base.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://homepages.paradise.net.nz/khemari/khemari/antarctic/antarctic.html|title=Emperor penguins at Scott Base: the coming of antarctic winter|last=Rodgers|first=Thelma|website=homepages.paradise.net.nz|access-date=2018-11-16}}</ref>
In 2017 a laboratory in the newly refurbished Hilary Field Centre at Scott Base was named after her.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thespinoff.co.nz/science/16-11-2018/celebrating-the-amazing-women-of-antarctica/|title=Celebrating the amazing women of Antarctica|date=2018-11-16|work=The Spinoff|access-date=2018-11-16|language=en-US}}</ref>
