{{Infobox military structure |name = Upper Battery |native_name = |partof = [[Fortifications of Gibraltar]] |location =[[Gibraltar]] |image = |caption = |map_type = <!-- Gibraltar --> |map_size = 300 |map_alt = |map_caption = Location in [[Gibraltar]] |type = [[Artillery Battery]] |coordinates = |code = |built = |builder = |materials = |height = |used = |demolished = |condition = |ownership = [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] |open_to_public = |controlledby = |garrison = |current_commander = |commanders = |occupants = |battles = |events = |image2 = |caption2 = }} '''Upper Battery''' is a former [[artillery battery]] in the [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] of [[Gibraltar]]. It was located on the Upper Ridge of the [[Rock of Gibraltar]] at a site south of [[Signal Hill Battery]] and faced east over the Mediterranean. It mounted two 32-pdrs. in 1861. On the other side of the hill, three 24-pdrs. were mounted at Lower Battery. The two batteries were used for signalling and drill purposes.<ref name="Hughes369">{{cite book|title=Strong as the Rock of Gibraltar|last1=Hughes|first1=Quentin|last2=Migos|first2=Athanassios|publisher=Exchange Publications|year=1995|page=369}}</ref>
The name "Upper Battery" was later used as a generic term for the three batteries mounting Gibraltar's main counter-bombardment guns, at [[Lord Airey's Battery|Lord Airey's]], [[O'Hara's Battery|O'Hara's]] and [[Spur Battery|Spur Batteries]].<ref name="Hughes369" />
